      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It's important to understand that the policies of the time were rooted in a specific, albeit flawed, social order. Proponents argued that segregation was necessary to maintain distinct cultural identities and prevent the dilution of established community norms. They believed that by keeping groups separate, social stability could be preserved, allowing each community to develop according to its own traditions without external interference. This perspective framed separation not as oppression, but as a form of necessary cultural self-preservation.",
